<BaseLayout title="Dog-Friendly Cafés, Pubs and Wineries Mornington Peninsula | Peninsula Insider" description="The Peninsula Insider guide to dog-friendly cafés, pubs and wineries on the Mornington Peninsula." section="eat">
  <main class="article-shell container prose" style="padding: 3rem 0 4rem; max-width: 820px;">
    <p class="label label--accent">Dog-Friendly Peninsula</p>
    <h1>Dog-Friendly Cafés, Pubs and Wineries on the Mornington Peninsula</h1>
    <p>A lot of venues say they are dog-friendly when what they really mean is that they will tolerate a dog if you stay outside and do not inconvenience anyone. That is not the same thing as a venue that genuinely works when the dog is part of the plan.</p>
    <p>The best dog-friendly Peninsula venues have enough outdoor space, enough airflow, and enough ease that the dog does not feel like a negotiation. They make the stop feel normal.</p>

    <h2>Cafés that actually work</h2>
    <ul>
      {cafes.map((venue) => <li>{venue}</li>)}
    </ul>

    <h2>Pubs and wineries worth building around</h2>
    <ul>
      {pubsAndWineries.map((venue) => <li>{venue}</li>)}
    </ul>

    <h2>The real rule</h2>
    <p>Across the Peninsula, the practical rule is consistent: assume outdoor only, on leash, and subject to current venue policy. A smart owner calls or checks bookings before treating any wine stop or lunch booking as guaranteed with the dog.</p>

    <h2>Best use cases</h2>
    <p><strong>For coffee after the dog beach:</strong> Mornington or Flinders pairings work best.</p>
    <p><strong>For a long lunch with the dog still in the plan:</strong> Red Hill and Main Ridge are the stronger zone, provided you book carefully.</p>
    <p><strong>For casual drinks without drama:</strong> the pub/beer-garden options are often easier than the more polished winery route.</p>

    <p>This page should keep deepening through verification. The editorial standard here is usefulness, not just inclusion.</p>
